n particular and social history in general, and provides detailed empirical studies of the Orange Order in Toronto, printers and their unions, the Knights of Labor, and the Canadian labour revolt of 1919. The collection concludes with three synthetic views of Canadian working-class history focusing on the labour movement, the role of strikes, and attempts by the state to manage class conflict. Workers and Canadian History will be of great interest to students and scholars of Canadian history, labour history, Marxist and socialist theory and history, and political science.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aLabor movementzCanadaxHistory. 0aWorking classzCanadaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh1 aCruikshank, Douglas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPalmer, Bryan D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356567840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773565678423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773565678/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles